## Nature

**Dragons** (Dovah, Dov in the plural) are not "creatures" in the biological sense. They are **fragments of Akatosh** — shards of the Time-God incarnated in reptilian form. Each dragon is:
- **Immortal** — does not age, does not die naturally
- **Unique** — each possesses a name in Dovahzul (the dragon tongue)
- **Intrinsically dominant** — dominion is their nature, not a choice

## Dovahzul

**Dovahzul** (the dragon tongue) is not a simple means of communication — it is a **language of power**. When a dragon speaks, its voice alters reality:
- Every word can become a **Thu'um** (Shout)
- The three words of a complete Shout are aspects of a concept
- For dragons, speaking AND fighting are the same thing (combat = debate)

### Examples of Shouts

| Shout | Words (Dovahzul) | Effect |
|-------|-----------------|--------|
| Unrelenting Force | Fus Ro Dah | Physical shockwave |
| Frost Breath | Fo Krah Diin | Icy breath |
| Fire Breath | Yol Toor Shul | Fire breath |
| Dragonrend | Joor Zah Frul | Forces temporary mortality |
| Call Dragon | Od Ah Viing | Summons an allied dragon |
| Slow Time | Tiid Klo Ul | Slows time |

## Draconic Hierarchy

Dragon society is a **meritocracy of power**:
- The strongest dominates (Thur = tyrant/sovereign)
- Submission is not a dishonor — it is nature
- Alduin is the **firstborn** and therefore the most powerful
- Dragons battle each other through the Voice as much as through claws

### Notable Dragons

| Dragon | Role | Status (4E 201) |
|--------|------|-----------------|
| Alduin | Firstborn, World-Eater | Defeated in Sovngarde |
| Paarthurnax | Alduin's lieutenant, then traitor | Alive, Throat of the World |
| Odahviing | Loyal dragon, then Dovahkiin's ally | Alive, free |
| Durnehviir | Trapped in the Soul Cairn | "Alive" (undead) |
| Mirmulnir | First dragon killed in 4E 201 | Dead (Western Watchtower) |
| Sahloknir | Resurrected by Alduin at Kynesgrove | Dead |
| Numinex | Captured by Olaf One-Eye | Dead (1E) |
| Nafaalilargus | Served Tiber Septim | Dead (2E) |

## The Dragon War (Merethic Era)

### The Tyranny
Dragons governed the humans of Tamriel as gods. The **Dragon Priests** served as intermediaries, imposing a brutal theocratic regime:
- Humans were slaves/worshippers
- Dragon Priests received powers in exchange for their service
- Resistance was punished by death through the Thu'um

### The Rebellion
Paarthurnax, persuaded by Kyne, taught the Thu'um to mortals:
- Humans learned to **Shout** against the dragons
- The war that followed lasted for generations
- The Shout **Dragonrend** — which forces the comprehension of mortality — was the decisive weapon
- Alduin was banished into the future by an Elder Scroll
- Surviving dragons scattered and entered hibernation

## Death and Soul Absorption

Dragons are quasi-immortal, but:
- They **can** be killed by physical means
- BUT a dead dragon can be **resurrected** by another dragon (Alduin did this)
- The only **permanent** death is **soul absorption** by a Dragonborn
- The Dragonborn absorbs the knowledge and power of the slain dragon
- This is why the Dragonborn is the only one who can truly defeat dragons

## The Return (4E 201)

Alduin, banished into the future by the ancient Nords, **reappeared** in 4E 201:
1. Arrival at the Throat of the World (interruption of an execution at Helgen)
2. Systematic resurrection of dead dragons throughout Skyrim
3. Reconstruction of his draconic army
4. Objective: devour the souls of Sovngarde, then the world
5. Defeated by the Last Dragonborn

## Draconic Philosophy

For a dragon:
- **To exist = to dominate** (the word "dragon" in Dovahzul means "dominion")
- **To speak = to act** (no separation between word and reality)
- **Strength** determines everything — there is no morality, only power
- **Time** is their domain — as fragments of Akatosh
- **Death** is incomprehensible — Dragonrend works because it forces this understanding
